If your pre-amp has an out, it may have a "direct monitor" feature which would allow you to hear. Otherwise I think you would need to go into your OS sound settings and "Listen to this device" to make the sound come out of your speakers, or headphones.

Also, record as quietly as you can; you can always raise volume but you can't really bring it back down. It'll take some experimentation to get it right, but it should be a kinda one-time thing (or at least something you can remember for the next time).

>Does Mono also rewrite crypto routines in C# or does it simply re-use the OpenSSL
>libs (which have optimized asm routines IIRC)?

The crypto support we ship is all implemented in C# and yes, it is slower than openssl's x86 asm routines, but (as is the case with python), speed is not always the only consideration. Having the code in C# means there is no external dependency, for example. There are also issues with certification (I can ask for details, I'm not the person dealing with the security/crypto stuff). And I'm not sure the semantics we needed to implement apply well enough to the openssl API or implementation (again, I can ask if this was a consideration).

I guess I was thinking of older versions of python, sorry about that.
Obviously the regex library needs speed improvements in mono and nobody was impacted by it enough to actually go and improve the code. If someoby was kind enough to run the regex-dna benchmark on a windows box with both the MS CLR and python and report the numbers, we could likely have a good estimate of the performance that could be achieved by mono, too, once the regex code is optimized.
